ENTRY            C3091   20251211   20260312   20260312       C253
SUBENT        C3091001   20251211   20260312   20260312       C253
BIB                  9         27
TITLE      Determination of the natTi(d,x)49V excitation
           function by liquid scintillation analysis
AUTHOR     (C.R.Kleinfeldt,V.S.Bodnar,S.D.Essenmacher,A.M.Miller,
           G.M.Brown,G.F.Peaslee,G.W.Severin)
INSTITUTE  (1USAMSU,1USANOT)
REFERENCE  (J,NIM/B,562,165652,2025)
           #doi:10.1016/j.nimb.2025.165652
FACILITY   (VDGT,1USANOT) The Nuclear Science Laboratory at the
           University of Notre Dame using a Pelletron tandem
           accelerator (HV FN type).
INC-SPECT  (EN-RSL) The beam was tuned to the energies within 1%
           uncertainty, and the current was recorded every
           second using a Digital Current Integrator (ORTEC 439
           Digital Current Integrator).
SAMPLE     A stack of thin titanium foils (Alfa-Aesar, 99.94%
           metals basis, 0.025 mm thick), containing four to
           eight foils each, depending on the incident deuteron
           beam energy. Each foil mid-thickness taken to be 7.15
           mg/cm2.
ANALYSIS   (DECAY) The cross-sections were calculated as:
           sigma=A/(I*rho*(1-exp(-lambda*t))), using the
           absolute activity (A) at the end of bombardment, the
           average deuteron current (I), the areal number
           density of the foil (rho), in atoms/cm2), the decay
           constant of the radionuclide of interest (lambda),
           and the irradiation duration (t).
HISTORY    (20251211C) BP
ENDBIB              27
NOCOMMON             0          0
ENDSUBENT           30
SUBENT        C3091002   20251211   20260312   20260312       C253
BIB                  6         22
REACTION   (22-TI-0(D,X)23-V-49,,SIG)
DETECTOR   (SCIN)
METHOD     (EXTB,CHSEP) Three separate irradiations were
           performed with incident deuteron energies of 8.00,
           7.00, and 4.75 MeV, respectively. Liquid
           scintillation analysis, in combination with the
           triple to double coincidence ratio (TDCR), also
           provides the ability to quantify radionuclides that
           decay solely by electron capture.
ERR-ANALYS (DATA-ERR) The cross-section uncertainty as
           determined by liquid scintillation analysis is
           estimated by propagation from the error associated
           with counting statistics (A), the areal density (pho)
           of the titanium foil, the beam current (I), uncertainty
            in the measurement used to determine the quench curve
            (3.33%), uncertainty in the TDCR determination (0.5%),
            and 5% uncertainty allotted for the differences in
           energy and intensity of the Auger electrons and X-rays
           emitted by 51Cr.
